comment: A decimal number is divisible by three iff the sum of its two "digits" is divisible by three. The term "digits" in its narrow sense is only correct if ` A ` and ` B ` actually are digits (i.e. nonnegative integers less than 10). However, this theorem holds for arbitrary nonnegative integers ` A ` and ` B ` , especially if ` A ` is itself a decimal number, e.g. ` A = ; C D ` . (Contributed by AV, 14-Jun-2021.) (Revised by AV, 8-Sep-2021.)
